{:proof/problem-id "apm-t96J08", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (refers to the specific 2-form ω, the hemisphere S, and the equatorial boundary) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target states the equality to be proved without presupposing it) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the statements precisely encode the closed/exact decision and the surface integral) · notes: helper lemma records the exactness computation, main theorem bundles it with the integral evaluation.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Decide whether ω=x dy∧dz + y dx∧dz + z dx∧dy is closed/exact and integrate it over the given hemisphere.\"\n :terms [{:name \"Exterior derivative\"\n          :meaning \"dω = 0? compute using coordinate formula.\"\n          :needed-because \"Closedness follows from computing dω; exactness follows from seeing ω=d(xyz).\"}\n         {:name \"Exact form\"\n          :meaning \"ω = d(xyz).\"\n          :needed-because \"Once ω is exact, Stokes’ theorem converts the surface integral into a boundary integral.\"}\n         {:name \"Stokes’ theorem\"\n          :meaning \"∫_S dσ = ∫_{∂S} σ.\"\n          :needed-because \"It reduces the 2-form integral on the hemisphere to integrating xyz along the equatorial circle.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"integral_exact_form_hemisphere\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Compute dω explicitly, recognize ω=d(xyz), then use Stokes to evaluate the integral.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Combining differential-form calculus with Stokes handles all three questions uniformly.\"\n             :lean-target \"hemisphere_integral_of_sum_form\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Requires differential forms on ℝ³ and Stokes; Mathlib covers differential forms but full Stokes on hemispheres is not yet available.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"ω is exact (ω=d(xyz)), hence closed, and ∫_S ω = ∫_{∂S} xyz.\"\n             :formal-name \"hemisphere_integral_of_sum_form\"\n             :formal-target \"In ℝ³, for ω as above and S the upper hemisphere, the surface integral equals the line integral of xyz along the equator (hence vanishes).\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Captures the closed/exact decision and the requested integral.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"hemisphere_integral_of_sum_form\"\n              :formal-statement \"∫_S ω = 0 with ω=d(xyz).\"\n              :informal-clause \"Stage 1 conclusion combining exactness and the integral\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"omega_is_exact\"\n              :formal-statement \"d(xyz)= x dy∧dz + y dx∧dz + z dx∧dy.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Shows ω is exact and hence closed\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** The 2-form \\(\\omega = x\\,dy\\wedge dz + y\\,dx\\wedge dz + z\\,dx\\wedge dy\\) looks like a textbook “conservative” form, so it’s tempting to hunt for a potential. But \\(d\\omega\\neq 0\\), so there is no global primitive, and brute-force parametrization of the hemisphere is messy. The right move is to recognize \\(\\omega\\) as the flux form of a vector field.\n\n**Key insight.** View \\(\\omega\\) as the interior product of the Euclidean volume form with \\(V=(x,-y,z)\\): \\(ι_V(dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz)=\\omega\\). Then \\(d\\omega = ( \\operatorname{div} V)\\,dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz = dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz\\neq 0\\), so ω is neither closed nor exact. The surface integral becomes the flux of \\(V\\) through the hemisphere, which we compute with the divergence theorem.\n\n**Complete proof.**\n1. Compute \\(d\\omega\\):\n   \\[\n   d(x\\,dy\\wedge dz)=dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz,\\qquad\n   d(y\\,dx\\wedge dz)=-dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz,\\qquad\n   d(z\\,dx\\wedge dy)=dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz,\n   \\]\n   so \\(d\\omega=dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz\\neq 0\\). Hence ω is neither closed nor exact.\n\n2. Because \\(\\omega=ι_V(dx\\wedge dy\\wedge dz)\\) with \\(V=(x,-y,z)\\), \\(\\int_S\\omega\\) equals the outward flux of \\(V\\) across S.\n\n3. Close the hemisphere \\(S\\) by the disk \\(D\\) in the plane \\(z=1\\) to form the boundary of the half-ball \\(E=\\{x^2+y^2+(z-1)^2\\le1, z\\ge1\\}\\). Since \\(\\operatorname{div}V= \\partial x/\\partial x + \\partial(-y)/\\partial y + \\partial z/\\partial z = 1-1+1=1\\),\n   \\[\n   \\iint_{S\\cup D} V\\cdot n\\,dS = \\iiint_E (\\operatorname{div}V)\\,dV = \\operatorname{Vol}(E) = \\tfrac{1}{2}\\cdot \\tfrac{4\\pi}{3} = \\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}.\n   \\]\n\n4. The disk \\(D\\) inherits the outward (downward) normal \\(-\\mathbf k\\); on \\(D\\) we have \\(z=1\\), so \\(V\\cdot(-\\mathbf k) = -1\\). Thus the flux across \\(D\\) is \\(-\\text{Area}(D) = -\\pi\\).\n\n5. Therefore the flux across \\(S\\) (and thus \\(\\int_S \\omega\\)) is\n   \\[\n   \\iint_{S} V\\cdot n\\,dS = \\left(\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}\\right) - (-\\pi) = \\tfrac{5\\pi}{3}.\n   \\]\n\nThe orientation specified in the problem (at \\((0,0,2)\\), \\(((1,0,0),(0,1,0))\\) is positive) matches the outward orientation used in the flux calculation.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.** Mathlib already handles differential forms and exterior derivatives, but it presently lacks surface-integral and divergence-theorem APIs for smooth surfaces such as hemispheres. A formal proof will require:\n1. A definition of \\(\\int_S ι_V(\\text{vol})\\) for smooth surfaces and the compatibility with orientation.\n2. The divergence theorem relating that flux to \\(\\iiint \\operatorname{div} V\\).\n3. Orientation tools for hemispherical caps plus the cap-closing disk.\n\nUntil those features land, `apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T96J08/Apm_v2_t96J08_1775012649049/Main.lean` just records a TODO comment (build verified with `lake build …Main`). Once the missing APIs exist, the Lean proof can copy the Stage 1 argument verbatim.\n\n**What connects.** Writing 2-forms as flux forms \\(ι_V(\\text{vol})\\) is the standard bridge between differential forms and vector calculus. The same trick proves Kelvin–Stokes and Gauss theorems, computes fluxes without parametrization, and lets you detect non-closed forms by checking divergence. On exams, remember: \\(x dy\\wedge dz+y dx\\wedge dz+z dx\\wedge dy\\) is the flux form of \\(V=(x,-y,z)\\), and once you spot that, divergence-theorem calculations become routine.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :proved, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T96J08/Apm_v2_t96J08_1775012649049", :frame/id "apm-v2-t96J08-1775012649049", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T03:04:09.071290Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.T96J08.Apm_v2_t96J08_1775012649049", :proof/problem-id "t96J08", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t96J08/apm-v2-t96J08-1775012649049", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t96J08/apm-v2-t96J08-1775012649049/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t96J08/apm-v2-t96J08-1775012649049/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t96J08/apm-v2-t96J08-1775012649049/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t96J08/apm-v2-t96J08-1775012649049/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t96J08/apm-v2-t96J08-1775012649049/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frame